dies on the use of intertextual writing strategies such as parody, contrafactum, or cento in the Latin literature of Europe from the 15th to the 17th century. They are based on new research approaches centering around text typology and the history of literary functions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aLatin literature, Medieval and modernxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aParody in literaturevCongresses. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh1 aCzapla, Beate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlei, Reinhold F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlei, Reinhold F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeckel, Iris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlecker, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKofler, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKühlmann, Wilhelm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Gernot Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiehl, Rüdiger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPieper, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobert, Jörg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaffenrath, Florian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeidel, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeidel, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Literary and Cultural Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110637854oZDB-23-GLC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET /